This is a PCR rack holder that tilts the rack 10° towards you, so that you can read the labels and see inside the wells without having to crane your neck. It accepts this kind of PCR tube rack, dimensioned at approximately 128 mm long, 88 mm wide, and 15 mm tall:

The pictured example is sold by Sigma-Aldrich, but the same basic design is sold as a rebranded item by many other sellers, for example here and here. Just look for the funny lugs on the sides of the rack, which means that it can hook into a PCR workstation.

You should add some self-adhesive rubber feet to the bottom of the holder when it's finished. Choosing tall feet will give the holder enough clearance from the table to fit skirtless 96-well PCR plates, with the wells poking through the big hole. Of course, skirtless plates fit straight into the racks themselves (as shown in the preview photo above), so it's your choice.

remixed_from.title: 127T change gear for cutting metric threads on a Harrison L5 lathe

title: 127T change gear to fit to 100T change gear

description.text:
This is a further refinement of my prior 127T design to enable machining of metric threads on Harrison L5 lathes. See my other designs for other lathe gear variations. http://www.thingiverse.com/nglasson/designs

The gear that this is re-mixed from takes a long time to print and it occured to me that it would be a simple matter to design a gear with 127T on the outside and 100T on the inside so it can be mounted on an existing steel 100T gear. Either the 100T or the 127T is normally mounted on the lead screw drive end so you wouldn't normally need to use both gears at once. This part is made in 4 segments so it can even be printed on a bed of 150mm square. I deliberately made the segments different sizes to avoid the chance of miss-assembly and to help if you want to nest them. All 4 pieces can easily be nested on a 200mm square bed.

I suggest that the complete 127T gear would be more convenient if you needed to switch between metric and imperial threadcutting, but if you mainly do one or the other, this option of a plug on to your 100T gear might be the answer.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Steelfence

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

I would suggest printing samples only to a few mm high initially to test the jigsaw fit and test the fit on the 100T gear. If too tight or too loose, there are two variables in the OpenSCAD file you can use to adjust the fit. 'SF' scales the 100T gear internal size and 'kerf' scales the gap in the jigsaw fit.

If the join fit is loose, secure parts together with glue and/or cable ties thru the 6mm holes adjacent to the joins. The other 4 holes are for cable tying to secure the 127T gear to the 100T gear (if your 100T gear has spokes). If you have a solid 100T gear, you could instead do two longer cable tie loops thru each pair of adjacent holes to prevent it slipping off. My make of this was a bit tight on the 100T gear so I had to spend 5 minutes with a thin file dressing the teeth on the plastic a bit. It is still a bit tight and probably won't need any cable ties.

I used my customizable change wheel design to create the base STLs and the most excellent puzzlecut code to do the separation into segments. WIth OpenSCAD you can tweak the code to suit your printer and then compile and save each segment in turn by commenting out the other 3 segments. Or you can save all at once and post process to separate.

description.text:
Simple plastic balls which have 6 conical-section holes, arranged through the centre and at right-angles to each other, allowing garden canes or sticks to be connected to make frames for peas or other climbing plants.

The holes are a convex cone-shape in section, tapering from 14mm down to about 6mm at the centre, meaning any cane from 14mm to 6mm will be able to find a point where it lodged/jams securely inside the hole.

This is based on some commercially available designs, and is a modification/simplification/upgrade on 'Garden Cane Corner' and 'Garden Cane Corner Middle' since this one part can be a corner OR a middle. I couldn't find any existing patents for this kind of thing so I think I'm probably OK sharing this design, but by all means if I'm infringing someone's IPR please let me know

Designed quick'n'dirty style in TinkerCAD. It's in the TinkerCAD Gallery Here's the share link

The STL file is a TinkerCAD export
The X3G file prints one ball, and takes about an hour on our Makerbot Replicator 2

I will (soon) upload a ready-made '6-up' or '8-up' print X3G (as soon as Makerware on Linux gets fixed) and in .gcode as well.

It took about 7 iterations before I got it to where it fit right & felt comfortable to hold. Now all makers can have a iPhone 7 case for around $1 - $2, It makes me love my 3D printer so much!!

I hope you guys enjoy & if your feeling generous you can add a tip! I will make some alternative case designs with different grips like hearts or circles in the future so check this model every so often for new updates.

Da Vinci Jr 1.0

Notes:

I print this case at 0.1 mm layer height with 30% infill to give a good amount of strength, it is holding an iPhone after all! I chose the Thick setting for the shells to give it another little boost of strength.

I printed them in white so an artist friend could add some cool designs easily to the back but if you print them in a darker color it will show less wear over time. You could always paint them as well.

A little light sanding on the outside and support removal both outside and inside. I also sand it slightly on the inside to make it smooth up against the phone to reduce the off chance of scratching. It fits so snug however that it is not likely to happen.

Stands for A5, A6 and trifold A4 folders and flyers. Meant for a use on a table, as opposed to a vertical setup.
Two sizes of stands are included. The sides are the same size for both; a connector is included to keep the stands together to form a rack.
The smaller size is meant for A6 or trifold A4, the larger one is for A5.

NOTE: apparently Thingiverse and some other tools don't render the SVG correctly; open the file with Inkscape and it should just work flawlessly.
The SVG includes all parts in one sheet so you will probably have to copy, paste and perhaps rotate them to accommodate the size of your lasercutter and material.
Lasercut this from 4 mm thick material; we've used MDF but acrylic would probably look especially nice.
Glue the parts together; make sure the sides are almost perfectly vertical if you want to neatly position them side by side.
Place adjoining stands in a connector piece; this, with the help of gravity, will keep them together.

Just a simple one folks, but could be handy. These brackets will adapt a 20mm Boom with as many elements as you like. There is an adapter for the director and reflector Elements and an adapter for the driven Element. These elements are 10mm diameter. The example photo I have provided is of a not very successful digital TV antenna I designed with the aid of software on the web (ie enter frequency and it spits out the dimensions). However I neglected to read the fine print and the dimensions of the tubes I used were a bit big for the frequency of digital television (eg 633MHz). The boom could have been 10mm and the elements should have been more like 2-4mm rods.
However it shows the general idea. If you are building a bigger antenna the current dimensions should be ok. Though don't attempt something too big, after all we are talking about printed plastic here!
I found the easiest way to mount the elements on the boom was to use 3mm stainless bolts and tap a thread into the aluminium boom.
Cheers, Rob.

description.text: This is a replacement part for a Aries custom fit car floor mats. The grommet comes in two pieces, a top and bottom. The top is pretty solid, the bottom is a very weak part. Mine broke when I was installing it, in fact, there are two and the second broke when I was taking the mat out to install the replacement, so now I have to print another one. It's not an exact match, but it's very close, works perfectly and is stronger than the original part. Please be aware, I don't know what other models this will work for - I have a 2011 Toyota 4Runner. My guess is that most Toyota mats will have the same kind of grommet, if not in the cars, at least in the trucks and other 4Runner model years. I called the manufacturer (Curt Manufacturing) to get a replacement and they sent me out the wrong piece. I let them know and instead of sending another they sent me a whole new floor mat. So the customer service is great and I love the floor mats, but I expected this part to fail repeatedly so I didn't even open up the new mats and just made this part instead. I hope it saves you some time.

description.text:
Outstanding Numbers were developed at the request of another Thingiverse member who wanted printable numbers to suspend from balloons and/or mount on a base to use as a trophy. These easy to print digits can be made as/when required for fun and to recognize an achievement or anniversary.

In addition to all 10 digits files have been included to mount either one or two as a trophy or prize. The bases have adjustment holes to allow the digits to be centred / spaced evenly. Print the numbers in any colour then pause at approx. 85% print progress to change the filament so the raised inner areas print in a different colour. It's easy... just watch for these inner surfaces to start building above the main number then pause / change.

Although these are easy to print please refer to the print instructions and images for additional information.

title: Heated Bed wire holder for Reprap heated bed

description.text:
I have had three prints ruined because one of the wires to my heated bed broke because of metal fatigue where the copper wires are soldered to the PCB heater bed. On my printer, the wires just dangle. As the printer moves in the Y direction, the wires bend and bend and eventually break. I thought of this general designa few weeks ago but I had taped the wires into a bundle and had thought that would fix it. Yesterday one of the wires broke anyway and a pokeball peeled up on one side.

So I printed this. This was my fourth attempt. Changes I made were:

  1. Properly fitting the hooks to the X frame.

  2. Making the main structure thinner to reduce the chance of warping, speed up printing, and reduce material used.

  3. The second to last attempt fit except that the part was not "tall" enough. Because of that, it put stress on the X frame. I realized installing it that it would possibly warp the hot plate and make the bed much harder to level. I added the box under the central tab. Now the fit is "relaxed".

I printed the part in ABS since it will be used by the heated bed. I want it to be more resistant to heat.

I used the "fantail" so that wire ties could be used without holes - but I decided to use a piece of electrical tape instead. But the fantail and various appendages make it vaguely look like a very abstract thunderbird.

If I knew how to make this parametric, I would set:

  1. The distance of the straight line. that is, the long rectangular piece.

  2. The angle of the arms.

  3. The size of the diamond arms that are going to the corners of the bed so that the size of the hook could be set.

  4. The thickness of the piece (distance between top of hook and flat tab.

  5. optional: The size of the fantail.

This object is sized for my reprap printer kit. I hope it will work for you.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

reprapguru kut

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.4mm nozzle, 0.2 layer

Infill:

22%

Notes:

I used 3 layers on the sides (1.2mm) and I started with 6 layers on top and bottom (1.2 mm) but then I changed it to 5 (1.0) with better results. The filament took 3 layers to bridge and fill in with 15% infill but the change to 22% infill relieved a lot of the bridging problems and the third laer was almost solid, while the fourth and fifth were solid and smooth. I believe that the best way to print this is to print it with the hooks up and support "touching buildplate". The only thing that needs support in that orientation is the tab. With the default settings in cura, the support breaks away cleanly and easily.

Printing it in that orientation with a very wide brim (I used 12 circles) on adhesive coated glass (mix of spray adhesive and hairspray) on a hot build plate (set to 124C) finally got the item to print with no warping. It took 1 hour, 27 minutes to print. I elected to print it diagonally - it probably would have barely fit oriented long way X or Y but the placement seemed easier this way.

Again, I used ABS because it is said to be more resistant to hot environments.

Installation

Other than removing the brim and supports, no trimming was required. The heat plate had to be completely removed to install it. If the x frame is warped at all, you should not leave it installed = bending the X frame might cause insurmountable leveling issues. If you can't remix it on tinkercad, give me the Thickness (z direction of your X frame and/or the distance along the straight piece and I will try to build you one (when I read my comments). The support should be slightly loose on the X frame and then the wires can be attached to the support using your favorite method, I guess you could use heat shrink if you cut the fantail or had massive heat shrink, or you could use wire ties or tape, The point is to eliminate the repeated flexing that causes the wires to fail because of metal fatigue, so the wires need to be firmly attached to the fantail.

I actually had two goals in designing this.

  1. To eliminate flexing at the solder joints.

  2. To allow for one of the wire management systems, like the chains, to have a place to mount, so that the wires would be protected from abrasion. I have not tackled that yet.

In my mind the shape of the piece was a simple composite of geometric shapes - rectangles and triangles. Thus, tinkercad became the obvious solution. I designed it using the current beta. It is called "reprap heated bed power wire holder" and my id there is nicksimicich.

title: Airsoft Top Dead Center mod for VSR-10 and APS2

description.text:
This is an airsoft mod.
Top dead center (TDC) mod for VSR-10 Gspec and APS2 (Like the L96) and possibly many more rifles. The vsr specific part goes on the outer barrel of 30mm diameter, the aps2 to a 25mm barrel.

Glue an M4 nut in the tdcvsr.stl or tdcaps2.stl and glue them on the barrel above the hole of the TDC. Glue the tdcbottom.stl on top of it.
Insert and if needed glue the outside ring of the tdcspring.stl into the tdctop.stl. An M4 screw must be able to move freely up and down in this assembly, but with possibly no side to side movement.

You can use an M4 screw with a hexa head or just screw a nut tighly on any M4 screw (That's what I did.)
Experiment with the length of the screw. The spring must be pushed about half way with the hopup set. That will keep the top nice and tight.

No support needed to print, print the top upside down.

UPDATE: I have changed the top to have finer clicks, the spring to be a bit stronger and the bottom to be higher to protect and guide the top better.
For me a 12mm hexa screw was perfect length.

title: Nozzle cooler regulated system for i3 Prusa/MK8 extruder (V3)

description.text:
Description

This is the height and angle regulated system for nozzle cooler for i3 Prusa clones with MK8 extruder.

You can change the height of the fan (and lock it) - so there is no problem when you change nozzle for any different model, or when you use different cooling conduct.

You can change fan angle, so it's output is perfectly parallel with the bed (mine has a bit skew mounting holes).

Additionally, you can use my cooling conduit - but you could probably find plenty more, here @ thingiverse.

Screws and Nuts :)

I have used computer screws (used widely when mounting any motherboard) to mount first plate to extruder carriage. But you can use any M3 screw that is short enough (probably 7mm or less).
You will also need an M3 nut for side locking mechanism (just push it in with vice or pliers), and corresponding screw. I used my old screws to attach fan - just needed to add 2 more M3 nuts.

Updates

  • I've added version with additional 0,25mm space between rails and lock (if standard version is to snug fit for your printer)
  • This is my third design of this system, but first release - so let's call it V3 :)

Infitary (hbi3) i3 Priusa clone

35% and more

Notes:

Print is quite easy, but there is a bridging. In my case this does not required supports, but it probably heavily depends on the printer settings.

You should set infill at 35% and more (so rails will stick hard enough to surface).

I used mostly PLA, but for nozzle cooling conduit ABS is recommended.
After printing there may be a need to easy edges of rails a bit. Just use a file or sandpaper - you should have not much work with it, if any.

An adapter for sticking a saxophone or clarinet mouthpiece onto 1/2" PVC pipe for making your own instrument-like-thing.

Someone gave me an old mouthpiece - I think it's from an alto sax, but I don't know for sure.  I made this simple OpenSCAD script for an adapter to plug the mouthpiece onto the end of a length of 1/2" (ID) PVC pipe.  It does the job.
This particular mouthpiece has a conical end, about 24 mm long, which tapers from 26.6 to 24 mm.  It should be easy to adjust the OpenSCAD file for slightly different shapes and sizes.

description.text:
A few more improvements May 2017. Latest tray has a mount for a tripod. Trying to hold the camera still underwater without a tripod makes lousy macro shots. I also added a focus stick for the +15 Macromate mini. Length is for a gopro 5 and gopro 4. with you thumb you can raise and lower the focus stick and and then press the shutter with your middle finger. These are big improvements. I left the old files up, but I suggest making the tray with the tripod adapter at 100% fill.

This is a gopro tray for use with 1 to 2 video lights with ball mounts. The Gopro on/off switch is located in an awkward position for use with a tray. Using other trays requires you to remove 1 hand from the handle and press the switch which is cumbersome underwater.

I have added a switch which can activate the gopro with your right thumb or your right index finger without taking your hands off of the handles. This results in much smoother transition and faster on/off cyles to assure you catch your shot.

This has been tested with the GoPro 3 in the Scuba Housing (not the standard housing). The arm may need to be modified for use with other housings.

I have levers for the Hero5 as well as the early versions.

The tray prints upside down, so that the smooth section is where the handles and gopro mounts. You will need a 1/4-20 or 6mm threaded gopro mount and 6mm x 30 stainless steel allen bolts and 6mm stainless steel nuts. Ideally, the switch is mounted with a ss 6mmx25mm bolt.

Printed with 0.3mm head in PLA at 0.2mm with 40%fill.

It has been tested to 95 feet (30m) and it did not crush even at 5% fill.

I think printing at 100% fill should solve this.  I originally used 30% fill to help make the rig more neutrally buoyant.  If it fills with water, you might as well use 100% fill.  It needs a tripod mount on the bottom to help steady macro shots.

This is a design concept for a stand that holds multiple spools of plastic for easy dispensing and reloading.  The idea is to use printable parts for the joints and a commonly found broom handle (1" diameter) for the support and axle.  
One 5ft. broom handle cut up into 5x1ft sections should produce a stand like the one pictured.  If you want to go bigger, you will need more than one broom handle.  Also, the feet have features for adding cross braces, if needed. 
This is 100% un-tested, and I wont be able to start printing until the end of March.  If anyone would like to test out the tolerances/stability, feel free.  Any documentation of your findings would be greatly appreciated.

• Print 4x Feet.STLs and 2x Yoke.STLs
  • Cut broom handles to desired length
  • Drill a screw into axle through the hole in one yoke to prevent rotation
  • Add spools of plastic and begin printing
  • Let me know how it goes

title: Tall X belt tensioner for Cobblebot (remix of I3_2020 design by drewprice)

description.text:
I needed a taller x-axis belt tensioner for my Cobblebot basic rescue project. This is a remix of drewprice's design using Tinkercad (my first remix!). Thank you, drewprice!!

I needed the taller tensioner to mate with parts of the the Cobblebot x-axis designs by CTHULHULABS (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1141077) and the remix by tomtom2770 (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1656664).

I made the base taller, enlarged the square hole to mate with the enlarged arm, and made the mounting holes larger for M5 screws. I enlarged the tensioner arm to accommodate the idler bearing assembly from openbuilds that uses an M5 screw for the axle (http://openbuildspartstore.com/smooth-idler-pulley-wheel-kit/).

The first articles here were made with BAMTack! white PLA at .2mm / 210 deg C / no supports with my stock FW DaVinci 1.0a and Simplify3D slicer. The final ones will be printed using black PetG on my Monoprice mini. As always, you may need to slightly increase or decrease the build size depending upon the filament and printer that you are using.

Printer:

DaVinci 1.0a; Monoprice Mini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20% or greater

Notes:

Pictured parts were run on my DaVinci 1.0a using BAMTack! white PLA at 210 deg C. Final parts will be printed in black PetG on my monoprice mini.

An adjustable height belt tensioner that sits on the 2020 extrusion and uses this idler pulley would be the real ticket. I may design one down the road (unless someone else beats me to it).
